Introduction¶

In this project, we will be gathering data from the Ford GoBike System. The goal for this project is to wrangle Ford GoBike System Data to create interesting and trustworthy analyses and visualizations.

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

On this data set we will be doing some data wrangling in order to make it tidy for analysis. There are multiple cities covered by the linked Ford GoBike System, and multiple data files will be joined together to compile all of 2017 & 2018.

This project is divided into two major parts. In the first part, we will conduct an exploratory data analysis on a dataset. We will using Python data science and data visualization libraries to explore the datasets variables and understand the datas structure, oddities, patterns and relationships. The analysis in this part will be structured, going from simple univariate relationships up through multivariate relationships. This project is our opportunity to ask questions of the data and make our own discoveries.

In the second part, we will take our main findings from this exploration and convey them to others through an explanatory analysis. To this end, we will create a slide deck that leverages polished, explanatory visualizations to communicate our results. This part of the project will make heavy use of the first part of the project. We will select one or two major paths in our exploration, choosing relevant visualizations along that path, and then polish them to construct a story for readers to understand what we found.

Part I - Gathering Data¶

Go Back To The Top

Gathering Data for this Project will involved the following:

  1. The Ford GoBike System Data is hosted at the Udacity servers and the all the files will be downloaded programmatically using the Requests library from the following URL: https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/index.html

  2. The download files are available in zip format. Therefore, we will programmatically extract the .csv files from the zip files and placed them in a separate directory within this project's directory.

  3. Once all the csv files have been downloaded and extracted, we will combine all the files into one data frame.

# programmatically download using pandas the data set file 2017-fordgobike-tripdata.csv
filename = '2017-fordgobike-tripdata.csv'
filePath = csv_files_dir+filename
# check if file already exists, if already exists do nothing.
#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/82831/how-do-i-check-whether-a-file-exists-without-exceptions

    print("[OK] File ", filePath, ' was previously downloaded')
else:
    file_url = files_url + filename
    print("File Name: '"+filePath+"' does not exist in this project.\nDownloading file: ", filename, " - Please wait...", end='\r')
    results = requests.get(file_url)
    with open(csv_files_dir+file_url.split('/')[-1], mode = 'wb') as outfile:
        if outfile.write(results.content):
            print("[Download Complete] File: " + filename + " ", end='\r')

# Downad all the 2018 zip files and extract the csv files to the data directory:
for month in range(1,13):
    month_string = str(month)
    # [MONTH] wil be replaced by the numerical month
    fileName = '2018[MONTH]-fordgobike-tripdata'
    month_leading_zero = month_string.zfill(2)
    fileName = fileName.replace("[MONTH]", month_leading_zero)
    
    csvFileName = fileName+ '.csv'
    zipFileName = fileName+'.csv.zip'   
    
    # check if file already exists
    #https://stackoverflow.com/questions/82831/how-do-i-check-whether-a-file-exists-without-exceptions
    if path.exists(csv_files_dir+csvFileName):
        print("[OK] File ", csvFileName, ' was previously downloaded')
    else:    
        b = "Downloading... " + "" + csvFileName
        print (b, end="\r")
        time.sleep(1)    
        #bike_data_url = 'https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/2018' + month_leading_zero + '-fordgobike-tripdata.csv.zip'
        file_url = files_url + zipFileName
        response = requests.get(file_url)
        # code below opens zip file; BytesIO returns a readable and writeable view of the contents;
        unzipped_file = ZipFile(BytesIO(response.content))
        # place extracted zip file into the data_files directory
        unzipped_file.extractall(csv_files_dir)
        print("[Completed]")
print('** Files Completed **')

# Check if Combined Master File has already been created, if not, then created it Programmatically
if path.exists(csv_files_dir+combined_csv_file_name):
    print("[OK] Combined Master File ", csv_files_dir+combined_csv_file_name, ' was previously created.')
else: 
    # Combine All Locally Saved CSVs into One DataFrame
    list_csvs = []
    month =1
    files = listdir(csv_files_dir)
    # https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38861829/how-do-i-implement-a-progress-bar
    f = FloatProgress(min=0, max=100)
    display(f)
    counter=0
    print('Combining all files into one Data Frame. Please wait...', end="\r")
    for file_name in files:
        #https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3964681/find-all-files-in-a-directory-with-extension-txt-in-python
        if file_name.endswith(".csv"):    
            #print('[Combining File.....] ', file_name, end="\r")
            list_csvs.append(pd.read_csv(csv_files_dir+'/'+file_name))
            #print('[Combining Completed] ', file_name)
            counter +=1
            f.value += counter
    df = pd.concat(list_csvs)
    f.value += 100 # make bar fully complete
    print('[Complete] All files combined successfully into one DataFrame')
    # IF YOU GET ERROR: ParserError: Error tokenizing data. C error: Calling read(nbytes) on source failed. Try engine='python'.
    # SOLUTION: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40835287/python-error-tokenizing-data-c-error-calling-readnbytes-on-source-failed-wi

Part III - Cleaning Data¶

Go Back To The Top

The 3rd step in data wrangling involves cleaning. Unclean Data: Dirty vs. Messy. There are two types of unclean data:

  1. Dirty data, also known as low quality data. Low quality data has content issues.
  2. Messy data, also known as untidy data. Untidy data has structural issues.

Cleaning is resolving quality and tidiness issues. We will identify these issues below.

Quality:¶

These are the issues will be evaluating to enhance the quality of our data:

  1. Make a copy of our dataframe
  2. Remove unnecessary columns
  3. Correct data types accordingly
  4. Calculate the age of the members and create a new column
  5. Create new columns to create new columns with more specific start and end time/date

# This function will be use to plot graphs.
def change_axis_format(tick_val, pos):
    if tick_val >= 1000:
        val = int(tick_val/1000)
        return '{:d}K'.format(val)
    elif tick_val >= 1000000: 
        val = int(tick_val/1000000)
        return '{:d}M'.format(val)
    else:
        return int(tick_val)

# Generate Hourly Usage and Frequency for 20-50 Age Group Heat Map
subscriber_hour_df = df_copy[(df_copy['member_age']>=20) & (df_copy['member_age']<50) 
                              &(df_copy['start_time_hour']>5)&(df_copy['user_type']=='Subscriber')
                             ].groupby(['start_time_week_abbr', 'start_time_hour']).agg({'bike_id' : 'count'}).rename(columns={'bike_id':'count'}).reset_index()
subscriber_hour_df['start_time_week_abbr'] = pd.Categorical(subscriber_hour_df['start_time_week_abbr'], categories=[ 'Sun','Mon','Tue','Wed','Thu','Fri','Sat'], ordered=True)
subscriber_hour_df['count_perc'] = subscriber_hour_df['count'].apply(lambda x: (x/subscriber_hour_df['count'].sum())*100)
subscriber_hour_df['rank'] = subscriber_hour_df['count_perc'].rank(ascending=False).astype(int)
subscriber_hour_df_pivoted = subscriber_hour_df.pivot_table(index='start_time_hour', columns='start_time_week_abbr', values='rank')
customer_hour_df = df_copy[(df_copy['member_age']>=20) & (df_copy['member_age']<40) 
                              &(df_copy['start_time_hour']>5)&(df_copy['user_type']=='Customer') 
                             ].groupby(['start_time_week_abbr', 'start_time_hour']).agg({'bike_id' : 'count'}).rename(columns={'bike_id':'count'}).reset_index()
customer_hour_df['start_time_week_abbr'] = pd.Categorical(customer_hour_df['start_time_week_abbr'], categories=['Mon','Tue','Wed','Thu','Fri','Sat', 'Sun'], ordered=True)
customer_hour_df['count_perc'] = customer_hour_df['count'].apply(lambda x: (x/customer_hour_df['count'].sum())*100) #male
customer_hour_df['rank'] = customer_hour_df['count_perc'].rank(ascending=False).astype(int)

Conclusions¶

Go Back To The Top

I thought this was going to be a straight forward and simple project based on all that I have learned from the previous projects. However, as I dived in deeper I came across some challenges with the syntax. Through patience and perseverance I was able to find the answers on-line with my friends google and stackoverflow.

As for this dataset, we started with 18 columns and added some time related columns to plot our data and make it more tidy. To be able to find the monthly, weekly, hourly data I had to create several additional columns to generate some interesting and informative columns which helped me create the graphs to visually present the data.

The data that was provided by the GoBike System seem to be an accurate usage representation of local commuters and tourists. I was able to learn that bike usage peak during commute hours for members, yet for non-member which are identified as tourist peak days seem to be during the weekend on Saturday and Sundays.

Another interesting piece of information I was able confirm during my observations is for the month of October. The San Francisco bay area is unique in that most of the year is foggy. However, during the month of October, we can enjoy fog-free weather and thus the best time to bike at golden gate park. With the bike share data, you can confirm that October has the highest ridership from any month of the year.

Overall this was a challenging project, but I learned alot from the research. I enjoyed it because I was able to related with the local area. I first visited the bay area in 2000. My co-workers invited me to visit. I felt in love with the Bay Area and I found a way to transfer from Denver. I've been living in the Bay Area for more than 19 years now and its an amazing place to live. Please don't take my word for it, I invite you to visit and see for yourself.
